{"pin":"BH11209","subcodes":[{"code":"BH11209","anchor":"","title":"Salat-i-Saghir (Short Obligatory Prayer)","first_line":"I bear witness, O my God, that Thou hast created me to know Thee and to worship Thee.","first_line_orig":"اشهد یا الهی بانک خلقتنی لعرفانک و عبادتک و اشهد فی هذا الحین بعجزی و قوتک  ","language":"1","word_count":"40","subjects":"@law of obligatory prayer, @power and sovereignty of God; omnipotence of God, @walking the spiritual path; spiritual wayfaring; the virtuous life, @importance of prayer, @purpose; goal of creation, @servitude; submission to God; repentance, @twin duties of recognition and obedience","notes":" \u003ca href=\"http://web.archive.org/web/20070930181707/http://bahai-library.com/resources/leiden.list/leiden.list.html#230\"\u003eLL#230\u003c/a\u003e","full_text_parts":["I bear witness, O my God, that Thou hast created me to know Thee and to worship Thee. I testify, at this moment, to my powerlessness and to Thy might, to my poverty and to Thy wealth. There is none other God but Thee, the Help in Peril, the Self-Subsisting.\n\n\n* \"The daily obligatory prayers are three in number. ... The believer is entirely free to choose any one of these three prayers, but is under the obligation of reciting either one of them, and in accordance with any specific directions with which they may be accompanied.\" - from a letter written on behalf of Shoghi Effendi \"By 'morning,' 'noon' and 'evening,' mentioned in connection with the Obligatory Prayers, is meant respectively the intervals between sunrise and noon, between noon and sunset, and from sunset till two hours after sunset.\" - Synopsis and Codification of the","Kitáb-i-Aqdas, p. 36"],"translations":[{"language":"sq","lang_name":"Albanian"},{"language":"sme-b","lang_name":"Northern Sami"},{"language":"fj","lang_name":"Fijian"},{"language":"kik","lang_name":"Gikuyu (Kikuyu)"},{"language":"arh","lang_name":"Arhuaco"},{"language":"pot","lang_name":"Potawatomi"},{"language":"tn","lang_na